<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-247-239 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 723 117</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  Jan 7 1991 p13D(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Santa Cruz Operation: a new Microsoft?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fisher, Lawrence M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Santa Cruz Operation Inc, an upstart company with revenues of $106million, markets one of the industry's fasting selling Unix-likeoperating systems.andP;  According to observers, the father-son team ofLarry and Doug Michels could be to the Unix world what Microsoftis to the MS-DOS world.andP;  The ever increasing popularity of 'opensystems' of which Unix has become the operating system of choice,puts the company into a position of advantage, because opensystems rely on the use of industry-standard software and hardwarethat give buyers an array of suppliers to choose from.andP;  The familyclaims that at first the concept of selling Unix on amicrocomputer was difficult, because the operating system was seenas being too complicated for a microcomputer.andP;  This changed whenIntel began to introduce more powerful microprocessors formicrocomputers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Santa Cruz Operation Inc. (Marketing).andO;Topic:     UNIX-Like Operating SystemsMarketing StrategyCompetitionIndustry AnalysisStrategic PlanningOperating SystemsOutlook.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Michels, Larry (Marketing); Michels, Doug (Marketing).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>